<body>
    <h1>1. Insecure Design</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><strong>Secure design</strong=
> </span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">is neither an add-on nor a tool=
 that you can add to software. </span><span style=3D"color: rgb(35,58,68);"=
>Secure Design is like a Safety Culture for Software:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Constantly Watching Out: </sp=
an><span>Imagine if building software were like building a fortress. Secure=
 design is like having </span><span>guards always watching</span><span> for=
 potential threats to your fortress. (</span><span>Example</span><span>: Wa=
tching one user giving wrong password 7 times. Consider this as unusual act=
ivity.)</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Making Strong Plans: </span><=
span>It's not just about building walls; it's about planning really well so=
 that even if someone tries to attack, your fortress (or software) can stan=
d strong. (</span><span>Example</span><span>: Lock this user for 10 mins)</=
span></p></li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>In the </span><span>user stor=
y development</span><span> determine the </span><span>correct flow and fail=
ure states</span><span>.&nbsp;</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Ensure the </span><span>resul=
ts are documented</span><span> in the user story</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Learn from </span><span>mista=
kes(if faced before)</span><span> and offer positive incentives to promote =
improvements.&nbsp;</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Get in touch with your securi=
ty specialists at the beginning of a software project throughout the whole =
project and maintenance of your software</span></p></li>
</ul>
<div>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"id-1.InsecureDesign-InsecureDesign:"><span>Insecure Design:</span=
></h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Notable Common Weakness:</span></p>
<ol>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>Generation of Error Messag=
e Containing Sensitive Information&nbsp;</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>Unprotected Storage of Cre=
dentials</span></p></li>
</ol>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3. Trus=
t Boundary Violation (</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">Data is =
not properly sanitized, validated</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">=
)</span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></strong></p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Shift-left Coding Practice</s=
pan></strong></p>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,=
0,0);">=E2=80=9CShift-left" is a concept in software development that invol=
ves integrating security practices earlier in the development process. Trad=
itionally, security considerations were addressed later in the development =
lifecycle, but "shift-left" promotes incorporating security measures as ear=
ly as possible, ideally during the coding phase.</span></span></span></span=
>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(=
0,0,0);">Factors Contributing to Insecure Design:</span></strong></span></s=
pan>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(=
0,0,0);"><br></span></strong></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><strong style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Lack of Business Risk Profil=
ing:&nbsp;</strong></span>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Not understanding the specific risks=
 and needs of the business when creating the software. It's like not realiz=
ing how important it is to </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,121,107);">have good locks</span>
<span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;"> on your doors.</span>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;"><br></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span><strong><span style=3D"color=
: rgb(35,58,68);">Failure to Determine Security Requirements:</span></stron=
g><span style=3D"color: rgb(35,58,68);"> </span></span></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,=
121,107);">If we don't really figure out </span><span style=3D"color: rgb(3=
5,58,68);">how much security</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(35,58,68);"> i=
s needed based on the risks, we might end up with a plan that doesn't prote=
ct against the right things.</span></span></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span><span class=3D"confluence-em=
bedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size"><img class=3D"confluen=
ce-embedded-image confluence-external-resource" height=3D"400" src=3D"https=
://lh7-us.googleusercontent.com/f_lTEAzk0gOu42kd2_mM5YkXui3seuoUS1mIIU7nLjh=
a2G5VGWZ-uAttnDX2OwIE1m9ZaIJnnqSkMwZeDXTVPJ_A31-9_jCLfjcb2CqTiufkvI1U69GbTb=
QpA3N4YKHHRRA-T3bQ9UBAkENL_GG2ub9EsQ=3Ds2048" data-image-src=3D"https://lh7=
-us.googleusercontent.com/f_lTEAzk0gOu42kd2_mM5YkXui3seuoUS1mIIU7nLjha2G5VG=
WZ-uAttnDX2OwIE1m9ZaIJnnqSkMwZeDXTVPJ_A31-9_jCLfjcb2CqTiufkvI1U69GbTbQpA3N4=
YKHHRRA-T3bQ9UBAkENL_GG2ub9EsQ=3Ds2048"></span></span></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(=
0,0,0);">Example1: </span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Credential Rec=
overy Workflow:</span></strong></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">A process designed to help users r=
egain access to their accounts in case they forget their passwords or are l=
ocked out.</span></p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">"Questions and Answers" Appro=
ach: </span></strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">The information =
required for&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">these questi=
ons is often personal and may be easily obtainable through&nbsp;</span><spa=
n style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">social engineering or online sources</spa=
n><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">. Multiple people might know the na=
me of a user's pet or their favorite color.&nbsp; So, this approach is proh=
ibited by NIST 800-63b, the OWASP ASVS, and the OWASP Top 10.&nbsp;</span><=
/p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">Recommendation:</span></st=
rong></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>The scenario recommends remov=
ing the code that implements the "questions and answers" approach and repla=
cing it with a more secure design. This could involve adopting more robust =
and multi-factor authentication methods, such as using one-time codes sent =
to a user's registered email or phone, biometric authentication, or other s=
ecure identity verification mechanisms.</span></p></li>
</ul>
<div>
<strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Example2:&nbsp;</span><span styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Group Booking Policy</span></strong>
</div>
<div>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">A cinema chain allows group booking d=
iscounts and has a maximum of fifteen attendees before requiring a deposit(=
not full amount). Attackers could threat model this flow and test if they c=
ould book six hundred seats and all cinemas at once in a few requests, caus=
ing a massive loss of income.</span></p>
<div>
<span><span><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">To address this threat, the cinema=
 chain can implement various mitigation measures:</span></p>
</div>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Rate Limiting: </span><span>I=
mplement rate limiting on the booking system to restrict the number of requ=
ests a user or IP address can make within a specific time frame. This helps=
 prevent a single user or automated script from overwhelming the system.</s=
pan></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Monitoring and Anomaly Detect=
ion:</span><span> Implement systems to monitor booking patterns and detect =
anomalies. Unusually large numbers of bookings within a short period can tr=
igger alerts for further investigation.</span></p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">&nbsp;User Authentication: </sp=
an><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">Require users to authenticate thei=
r identity before making large bookings. This additional layer of verificat=
ion can help ensure that bookings are legitimate.</span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);"><br></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><strong><span style=3D"color=
: rgb(0,0,0);">Example3: </span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Online s=
tore<br></span></strong></span></span></span>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">There is a problem with a retail chai=
n's online store that sells high-end video cards. Scalpers are using comput=
er programs (bots) to quickly buy up these video cards in large quantities =
with the intention of reselling them at higher prices on auction websites. =
This is causing frustration among genuine customers, as they are unable to =
buy the video cards at regular prices.</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0=
,0,0);">Proposed Solution:</span></strong></p></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">To address this issue, the suggestion=
 is to implement careful anti-bot measures on the website. These measures i=
nclude:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;"><p><span>Anti-Bot Design:</span></p></=
li>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>The website should be designe=
d in a way that makes it difficult for automated bots to make purchases. Th=
is could involve implementing security features that can distinguish betwee=
n human users and automated scripts.</span></p></li>
</ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;"><p><span>Domain Logic Rules:</span></p=
></li>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Set up specific rules or cond=
itions (domain logic rules) that help identify suspicious transactions. For=
 example, purchases made within a few seconds of a product becoming availab=
le might be flagged as potentially inauthentic.</span></p></li>
</ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;"><p><span>Transaction Rejection:</span>=
</p></li>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>If a purchase is identified a=
s potentially being made by a bot or falls under suspicious conditions, the=
 transaction should be rejected. This means the scalpers' attempts to buy i=
n bulk for resale would be unsuccessful.</span></p></li>
</ul>
</ul>
</div>
<div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);"><strong><span style=3D"color: r=
gb(15,15,15);"><span><br><br><br></span></span></strong></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span><span><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);"><strong><span=
 style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);">Security Principles:</span></strong></span=
></span></span></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span><span><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15);"><strong><span=
 style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></strong></span></span></span></sp=
an></span>
</div>
<div>
<span><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);letter-spacing: 0.0px;">1. <st=
rong>The principle of Least Privilege and Separation of Duties:</strong></s=
pan></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Least Priv=
ilege </span></strong>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">is a security principle that states that=
 users should only be given the </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">minimum amount of access </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">necessary to perform their job. This mea=
ns that users should only be given </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">access to the resources they need </span=
>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">to do their job, and no more. This helps=
 to reduce the risk of </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">unauthorized access to sensitive data or=
 systems</span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">, as users are only able to access the r=
esources they need.</span>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span>
</div>
<div>
<strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Separation=
 of Duties</span></strong>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"> is a system of checks and balances that=
 ensures that </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">no single individual has control over al=
l aspects of a transaction.</span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"> This is done by assigning different tas=
ks to different people, so that </span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">no one person has control over the entir=
e process</span>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">. This helps to reduce the risk of fraud=
 and errors, as well as ensuring that all tasks are completed in a timely m=
anner.</span>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span>
</div>
<div>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">2.The principle of Defense-in=
-Depth:</span></strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">It is based on the idea that if one l=
ayer of security fails, the other layers will still be able to protect the =
asset.&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Physical Security: </span><sp=
an>This includes controlled access to the </span><span>data center or serve=
r room </span><span>through keycard access, biometric authentication, and s=
urveillance cameras. Only authorized personnel have physical access to crit=
ical infrastructure.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Network Security: </span><spa=
n>Safeguards implemented at the network level, including firewalls and secu=
re network configurations.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Application Security: </span>=
<span>Protective measures applied to software and applications, involving s=
ecure coding practices, regular security testing, and secure application ar=
chitecture.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Data Security: </span><span>M=
easures to secure sensitive data, including encryption, access controls, an=
d data backup and recovery mechanisms.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>User Education and Awareness:=
&nbsp;</span><span>Training programs and awareness campaigns are conducted =
to educate users about security best practices. This includes recognizing p=
hishing attempts, using strong passwords, and understanding the importance =
of adhering to security policies.</span></p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(15,15,15=
);">Security information and event management (SIEM)</span><span style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(15,15,15);"> systems are used to analyze log data and detect anom=
alies that may indicate a security incident.</span></span></span>
</div>
<div>
<span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span>
</div>
<div>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">3. The principle of Zero Trus=
t</span></strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">It is based on the idea that organiza=
tions should not trust any user, device, or network, even if they are insid=
e the organization=E2=80=99s network. Instead, all requests for access must=
 be authenticated and authorized before access is granted. Zero Trust also =
requires organizations to continuously monitor and audit user activity to e=
nsure that access is only granted to those who need it.</span></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></p>
</div>
<span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><br></span></span>
</div>
    </div>
